---
/**
 * Local income tax hub. Twelve states levy something below the state line, and
 * the point of this page is that they do it in eight different shapes — so the
 * question "what's the local rate?" has no answer in half of them.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { states } from '../../data/states';
import { stateSlug } from '../../lib/slug';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';
import { localTaxStates, localTaxFor, localRange, ohioCreditTraps, reachesSelfEmployment } from '../../lib/local-tax';
import { localCopyFor } from '../../data/local-tax-copy';

const EXAMPLE = 80000;
const codes = localTaxStates();

const rows = codes.map((code) => {
  const d = localTaxFor(code)!;
  const range = localRange(code, EXAMPLE);
  return {
    code,
    name: states[code].name,
    reachesSE: reachesSelfEmployment(code),
    headline: localCopyFor(code)?.headline ?? '',
    range,
  };
});

const traps = ohioCreditTraps();
---

<Base
  title="Local income tax by state (2026) — the city and county taxes on top of state tax"
  description="Twelve states let cities, counties and school districts tax income on top of the state. Which they are, what they charge in 2026, and whether they reach self-employment profit."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Local income tax, state by state</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Twelve states tax income below the state line. Most calculators stop at the state.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Federal, then state, then — in twelve states — a third layer your city, county or school district
    charges on top. It is small enough to ignore in some places and larger than the state tax in others: a
    Philadelphia resident pays more to Philadelphia than to Pennsylvania, because Pennsylvania's flat rate
    is 3.07% and the city's is 3.74%.
  </p>
  <p>
    There is no single "local rate" to look up. Across these twelve states the charge takes eight different
    shapes. Some are a percentage of income. Yonkers charges a percentage <em>of your state tax</em>. New
    York City has its own bracket schedule. Huntington, West Virginia charges $5 a week regardless of what
    you earn. Portland charges $35 a year, flat. Ohio charges a rate and then partially credits what you
    paid somewhere else — and the size of that credit is not the same in any two cities.
  </p>

  <h2>Where local income tax exists</h2>
  <p>
    What a levy costs on {formatMoney(EXAMPLE)}, from the cheapest jurisdiction in the state to the most expensive.
    A wide range means the state has no useful average:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>State</th>
        <th>On {formatMoney(EXAMPLE)}</th>
        <th>Reaches self-employment profit?</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {rows.map((r) => (
        <tr>
          <td><a href={`/local-income-tax/${stateSlug(r.name)}/`}>{r.name}</a></td>
          <td>
            {r.range === null
              ? 'flat dollars, not a rate'
              : r.range.low === r.range.high
                ? formatMoney(r.range.low)
                : `${formatMoney(r.range.low)} – ${formatMoney(r.range.high)}`}
          </td>
          <td>
            {r.reachesSE === true ? 'Yes' : r.reachesSE === false ? 'No — wages only' : 'Not confirmed'}
          </td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>The self-employment column is the one to read</strong>
    Local rules for self-employment net profit are frequently different from the wage rule, and the
    difference cuts both ways. Pennsylvania's earned income tax reaches a sole proprietor's Schedule C
    profit but <strong>not</strong> an S-corp owner's distributive share — which makes the S-corp election
    worth materially more in Pennsylvania than the federal arithmetic alone suggests. Ohio taxes net profit
    in full and does not let you use the state Business Income Deduction against it. Where a state is
    marked "not confirmed" it means exactly that, never that the answer is no.
  </div>

  <h2>The trap in each of the twelve</h2>
  <p>
    None of these states is straightforward, and the thing that catches people is different in every one.
    Open one for the short version, or follow the link for how the charge is actually worked out:
  </p>
  <div class="accordion">
    {rows.filter((r) => r.headline).map((r) => (
      <details>
        <summary>{r.name}</summary>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>{r.headline}</p>
          <p><a href={`/local-income-tax/${stateSlug(r.name)}/`}>Local income tax in {r.name} →</a></p>
        </div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>
  <p>
    Ohio's is the one that changes the answer by direction rather than by amount: in {traps.length} of its
    twenty largest cities the credit for tax paid to another city is capped below the city's own rate, so
    a resident working elsewhere still gets a bill.
    {' '}<a href="/local-income-tax/ohio/">The cities and the figures are on the Ohio page</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>The thirty-eight states with none</h2>
  <p>
    Everywhere not listed above, the state return is the last one. If you live in one of the twelve, the
    local charge is usually not withheld when you are self-employed — no employer means no withholding —
    and it is due on the same quarterly rhythm as everything else.
  </p>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 tax calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly payments</a></li>
    <li><a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/">S-corp election</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    This is general information about how these taxes work, not tax advice. Local rates change by
    ordinance and referendum more often than state rates do — check with your own jurisdiction or a tax
    professional before relying on any figure here.
  </p>
</Base>
